PCA and t-SNE Project: Auto MPG¶

Marks: 30¶

Welcome to the project on PCA and t-SNE. In this project, we will be using the auto-mpg dataset.

Context¶

The shifting market conditions, globalization, cost pressure, and volatility are leading to a change in the automobile market landscape. The emergence of data, in conjunction with machine learning in automobile companies, has paved a way that is helping bring operational and business transformations.

The automobile market is vast and diverse, with numerous vehicle categories being manufactured and sold with varying configurations of attributes such as displacement, horsepower, and acceleration. We aim to find combinations of these features that can clearly distinguish certain groups of automobiles from others through this analysis, as this will inform other downstream processes for any organization aiming to sell each group of vehicles to a slightly different target audience.

You are a Data Scientist at SecondLife which is a leading used car dealership with numerous outlets across the US. Recently, they have started shifting their focus to vintage cars and have been diligently collecting data about all the vintage cars they have sold over the years. The Director of Operations at SecondLife wants to leverage the data to extract insights about the cars and find different groups of vintage cars to target the audience more efficiently.

Objective¶

The objective of this problem is to explore the data, reduce the number of features by using dimensionality reduction techniques like PCA and t-SNE, and extract meaningful insights.

Dataset¶

There are 8 variables in the data:

  • mpg: miles per gallon
  • cyl: number of cylinders
  • disp: engine displacement (cu. inches) or engine size
  • hp: horsepower
  • wt: vehicle weight (lbs.)
  • acc: time taken to accelerate from 0 to 60 mph (sec.)
  • yr: model year
  • car name: car model name

FEATURE ENGINEERING: Columns 'model year' and 'car name' have space in the header, which can cause problems in the dataset analysis so we are changing the name 'model year' to 'year' and 'car name' to 'brand'. Also we will change the column name 'horsepower' to 'hpwr', 'acceleration' to 'accl', and 'displacement' to 'disp' to save space.

In [284]:
data.rename(columns={'model year': 'year'}, inplace=True)
data.rename(columns={'car name': 'brand'}, inplace=True)
data.rename(columns={'horsepower': 'hpwr'}, inplace=True)
data.rename(columns={'displacement': 'disp'}, inplace=True)
data.rename(columns={'acceleration': 'accl'}, inplace=True)

FEATURE ENGINEERING: The column 'cylinders' has only five unique values namely 3,4,5,6,8. It would have made sense to convert this variable into a categorical variable or 'object'. However, car experts would disagree. They would explain that the number of cylinders is quantifiable and directly affects the performance of the car, for example displacement and consequently horsepower and acceleration. So we will not change the variable type of column 'cylinders'. But becuase year is a time instance and should not be analyzed as integer so we will convert column 'year' to an object. On the other hand, as discussed earlier, we should convert the 'hpwr' column to a numerical column so we can analyse it further by finding its mean, min and max values etc.

In [290]:
data['year'] = data['year'].astype(object)
data['hpwr'] = data['hpwr'].astype(int)

The boxplots are very informative. We can tell that there are no outliers in cylinders, displacement, weight, and year. Acceleration has a few outliers on either side. Horsepower has a significant number of outliers on the high end. Data for acceleration seems to be normally distributed. almost every other column is slightly skewed to the right. Please note that the error above is for the plot for 'brand', we can ignore this since we do not need a plot for brand.

Now lets look at heat map data to see correlation between different variables.

In [438]:
plt.figure(figsize = (15, 5))

sns.heatmap(data.corr(numeric_only = True), annot = True, fmt = '0.2f')

plt.show()

**OBSERVATIONS: We only have 6 numerical variables. Based on that, it looks like the data is highly correlated. We can make the following observations from the heatmap above:

  1. There is high negative correlation between mpg and all all other variables except **accl. Which makes sense as, automobile experts would agree that these variables will increase the fuel consumption of the vehicle so the mpg would reduce.

  2. On the other hand, cylinders-displacement are highly positively correlated which makes sense. The higher the cylinder count, typically, the higher chance of total displacement.

  3. Similary weight-displacement and weight-cylinders also have a high positive correlation. All variables except weight have a positive correlation with accl.

t-SNE¶

In [363]:
for i in range(10, 50, 5):
    tsne = TSNE(n_components = 2, random_state = 1, perplexity = i)
    
    data_scaled_tsne = tsne.fit_transform(data_scaled)
    
    data_scaled_tsne = pd.DataFrame(data_scaled_tsne)
    
    data_scaled_tsne.columns = ['X1', 'X2']
    
    plt.figure(figsize = (7,7))
    
    sns.scatterplot(x = 'X1', y = 'X2', data = data_scaled_tsne)
    
    plt.title("perplexity = {}".format(i))

Observations: Data is clearly grouped into atleast 3 separate groups. Graphs above with perplexity 20 and higher are good at distinguishing between different groups. def grouping(x):
    first_component = x['X1']
    
    second_component = x['X2']
    
    if first_component < -2:
        return 'Group1'
    
    elif (first_component > -2) and (first_component < 18): 
        return 'Group2'
    
    else: 
        return 'Group3'
    
data_scaled_tsne['Groups'] = data_scaled_tsne.apply(grouping, axis = 1)

Observations: There are 3 groups in the data set. Group1 represents most fuel efficient vehicles. They have the lowest specs such as weight, displacement, which results in higher values of mpg(miles per gallon of fuel).

Group3 is the opposite with least values of mpg because they are most performance oriented cars.

Group2 however is somewhere in between.

Actionable Insights and Recommendations¶

write your insights and recommendations here:

One thing to observe from the last plot is that the vehicle's efficiency seems to be improving as the model year goes from older to newer.

Typical vintage vehicles that the dealership has sold can be grouped into three groups which can be understood to be performance based classes.

Group 1 contains almost half of the entire dataset which has the least variation in the engine displacement. This group can be marketed as high performance 'sporty' options. Even within this group, we have plenty of options of mpg or year of manufacture so the customers can easily be attracted to this class.

If we were to assign selling prices to the cars, we should keep in mind that group2 and group3 will not give us much flexibility in price range. We can experiment with a wide pricing range only for group1. For the same reason, group1 cars can offer promotional pricing from time to time to incentivize increased sales.
